%
Safety first. In allocating resources, strive to avoid disaster rather than to
attain an optimum. Many years of experience with virtual memory, networks, disk
allocation, database layout, and other resource allocation problems has made it
clear that a general-purpose system cannot optimize the use of resources.
[38;5;8m - Butler W. Lampson (1983)[0m
%
Shed load to control demand, rather than allowing the system to become
overloaded. There are many ways to shed load. An interactive system can refuse
new users, or even deny service to existing ones. A memory manager can limit
the jobs being served so that all their working sets fit in the available
memory. A network can discard packets. If it comes to the worst, the system can
crash and start over more prudently.[38;5;8m - Butler W. Lampson (1983)[0m
