A good heuristic for designing programming languages is to try to take the
largest most complicated kinds of things you want to do, work them out, and
then see if there is a "language lurking". Most people make the big mistake of
lovingly making small neat examples that are easy to learn - these often don't
scale at all well. E.g. "data" in the small "seems natural" but the whole idea
scales terribly. And so forth for most of the favorite paradigms around today.
