Pike's 1st Rule: You can't tell where a program is going to spend its time.
Bottlenecks occur in surprising places, so don't try to second guess and put in
a speed hack until you've proven that's where the bottleneck is.
[38;5;8m - Rob Pike, Notes on C Programming (1989)[0m
%
Pike's 2nd Rule: Measure. Don't tune for speed until you've measured, and even
then don't unless one part of the code overwhelms the rest.
[38;5;8m - Rob Pike, Notes on C Programming (1989)[0m
%
Pike's 3rd Rule: Fancy algorithms are slow when n is small, and n is usually
small. Fancy algorithms have big constants. Until you know that n is frequently
going to be big, don't get fancy.[38;5;8m - Rob Pike, Notes on C Programming (1989)[0m
%
Pike's 4th Rule: Fancy algorithms are buggier than simple ones, and they're
much harder to implement. Use simple algorithms as well as simple data
structures.[38;5;8m - Rob Pike, Notes on C Programming (1989)[0m
%
Pike's 5th Rule: Data dominates. If you've chosen the right data structures and
organized things well, the algorithms will almost always be self-evident. Data
structures, not algorithms, are central to programming.
[38;5;8m - Rob Pike, Notes on C Programming (1989)[0m
