The preconditions of revolution exist in the UK, and most western countries.
The number of active pre-conditions is quite stunning, from elite isolation to
concentrated wealth to inadequate socialisation and education, to concentrated
land holdings to loss of authority to repression of new technologies especially
in relation to energy, to the atrophy of the public sector and spread of
corruption, to media dishonesty, to mass unemployment of young men and on and
on and on. [...] Preconditions are not the same as precipitants. We are waiting
for our Tunisian fruit seller. The public will endure great repression,
especially when most media outlets and schools are actively aiding the
